        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Springfield Ills November 1878<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd S. Morais<lb/>
                Philadelphia Pa.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#33;  Although a perfect stranger to you&#44; I take<lb/> the liberty to address these lines to you&#44; as an<lb/> explanation to the enclosed slips from our local<lb/> papers.  Since nearly 40 years an ardent student<lb/> of Church Music in general and Hebrew &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> in particular&#44; I have been encouraged by some<lb/> friends&#44; when attending the Milwaukee Council&#44;<lb/> to revive my musical studies as to our ancient<lb/> Traditional Melodies and to assist in a future<lb/> effort to gather them&#44; thus to metamorphose them<lb/> from &#91;Hebrew&#93; to &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I have spent the<lb/> last 6 or 8 months in the study of this&#44; my old<lb/> hobby&#34;&#34;and the first fruit in the lecture by<lb/> invitation of a Christian Church.  To still<lb/> augment my collection&#44; I like to study the<lb/> &#34;Portuguese&#34;¬ù melodies and in order to attain this desired<lb/> end&#44; I would most respectfully ask you&#44; whether there<lb/> are musical works printed&#44; which contain the Portug.<lb/> Liturgy&#8212;not only a few Hymns or Pintim&#91;&#63;&#93;&#44; but<lb/> <hi rend="underline">the</hi> Liturgy&#8212;Psalm &#91;&#63;&#93;&#44; Canticles and all.<lb/></p>
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>are there&#44; besides the music&#44; works in either<lb/> Hebrew&#44; <sic>french</sic> or Italian&#34;&#34;treating on the<lb/> subject&#44; so as to enable me to get acquainted<lb/> with the Liturgy&#63;  I understand somewhat these<lb/> 3 languages and I believe&#44; I could even work my&#45;<lb/>self into the <sic>spanish</sic>&#44; if a work should be<lb/> written in that language.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping you will kindly excuse me<lb/> from addressing you&#44; I do so on the suggestion<lb/> of my friends Dr Sonnerheim in St Louis and<lb/> Dr Wise in Cincinnati&#44; to whom I am permitted<lb/> to refer.<lb/></p>
            <p>Please God&#44; I intend to visit the<lb/> East next summer for the conference&#44;<lb/> when&#34;&#34;with your permission&#8212;I shall<lb/> have the honor to pay you a visit and<lb/> make your personal acquaintance.<lb/></p>
            <p>To disabuse you from any<lb/> <hi rend="underline">high</hi> opinion&#44; you may form about me<lb/> as to my &#34;erudition&#44; deep scholarly<lb/> learning&#44; L&#91;&#63;&#93; I beg to state&#44;<lb/> that I am a Merchant now&#44; and 22<lb/> years ago was a&#8212;Chasan.  But I<lb/> have retained my love for Jewish Affairs<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>and especially Hebrew music and am<lb/> constantly connected with everything&#44;<lb/> that tends to make our Holy Religion<lb/> more deeply rooting in the hearts of our<lb/> co&#45;religionists.<lb/></p>
            <p>Again asking your pardon for<lb/> my intrusion upon your time&#44; I am&#44;<lb/> Revd Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours most Respectfully<lb/>
                G S Ensel.<lb/></p>
        </body>
